media:group.media:title: Discover Stanford for You: Accelerating Solutions for Global Sustainability
media:group.media:description:
How do Stanford researchers collaborate with partners to solve some of our most pressing sustainability problems? This program highlights the high-impact work of Stanford faculty who are working with partners locally and globally to tackle urgent planetary challenges.
This September, the Stanford Doerr School of Sustainability launched as the university‚Äôs first new school in 75 years. A key feature of the new school is its sustainability accelerator, which seeks to develop near-term policy and technology solutions to global needs in sustainability. Learn how Stanford faculty from across the university are working alongside practitioners to co-create and scale solutions for climate and sustainability challenges that threaten people globally. This virtual event was co-sponsored by Stanford Continuing Studies and Stanford Office of External Relations.

entry.title: Day in the Life: Carly Mae Smith, '23

media:group.media:title: Day in the Life: Carly Mae Smith, '23
media:group.media:description:
Experience a day in the life of Stanford undergraduate Carly Mae Smith, ‚Äô23, as she conducts summer research in the Heller Lab at the Wu Tsai Human Performance Alliance.
Working on the fourth floor of the Gilbert Biological Sciences Building, Smith has been operating treadmill tests to measure how bodies respond to high-heat environments during exercise, and to gauge the effectiveness of new mitigation technologies that could assist fire fighters and other affected professionals.
Carly grew up on a cow farm in the small mountain town of Rocky Mount, Virginia, and this fall will start her last year as a human biology major at Stanford.
For more on undergraduate research opportunities at Stanford, visit: https://undergradresearch.stanford.edu/
